The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the request to abolish, within the framework of a novelty of the Criminal Code, the paragraphs on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the detained Prime Minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the application for mitigation of penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet in force, the appeal of the convicts to the courts is scheduled for December.
Timoshenko himself referred to the verdict as political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised the suspicion of bias of the court.
The request, Section 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted to remove from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
