The menu of a fat-addicted child: it does not eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This once again shows how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as often on the table as in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had potatoes for dinner on the eve of the enlightenment campaign under the motto "obesity is not a coincidence".
In families with thickheads, sports is not exactly one of the favorite occupations, but it also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year at the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being interviewed.
This was the second year of the “Obesity is not a coincidence” campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students from the 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the frightening increase in the number of children with obesity or even obesity.
“Only half of the children surveyed reported, for example, eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-dinner-dinner bread five times a day – one of the main requirements for a healthy diet,” according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of pupils’ families eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
The worst of all was the finding that in every tenth family there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey test revealed that unhealthy potatoes are much more often consumed in families of overweight children.
And almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do - that is, only 15 percent.
Set up your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal plan based on the opportunities offered in terms of appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sweet lemonades is alarming," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, the main dish, pasta won just before poultry.
The children almost didn't like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of the survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the enlightening lecture "Adiposity is not a coincidence", in many cases, there was a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating," the results of the project indicate.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give preference to ordinary water.
The children also crossed poultry or fish much more often in the questionnaire as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less noodles or sweet foods.
Professionals claim - a stylist must also be a good psychologist
In the introductory article on how stylists learn, I had a little bit of a grudge that this was a bit too much fabric for the beginning.
