Boylike figures can, in turn, allow themselves to wear clothing with folds, bushes, applications, embroidery or riveting.
With this amount of information and figure types, I’m glad I have a whole week of time to let everything go through my mind.
And yet I am afraid that given the assigned homework, it is almost impossible to do.
Each of the participants was assigned a celebrity, for which she was to come up with suitable outfits - daywear and evening dresses.
In doing so, we should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the corresponding star and its figure type.
I'm supposed to "dress" Miranda Kerr, who you might know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
Inside, I’m cheering, because that’s much better for me personally than, for example, dressing Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has probably gained a hundred kilos lately (well, that’s a bit exaggerated), or also the young Selena Gomez.
We are supposed to cut the garments out of magazines or search on the Internet, print them out and then graphically edit them.
In the "moodboard", as the whole result is called, our very personal style and our relationship to the graphic design should then be expressed.
It is very important to also think about the graphic side of styling.
In fact, the stylist not only attracts the models physically, but also designs the so-called product page in the journals (according to specific specifications, for example, trend handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about this.
But that's only on Sunday.
This means that a stylist must have a good overall overview.
The Saturday lecture, filled with information about figure types, was equally spiced by three visitors from the industry:
by stylist Jan Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Ren<0xC4><0x8D>.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and that a stylist should be able to take advantage of it.
And embedded stylist can work with a single piece of clothing in very different ways.
The magic word is variability.
For example, you can wear a trench coat as usual over the jeans, like a t-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on the naked body, put on heels and wear it as a dress.
All you need to do is crawl up your sleeves or collar and the whole look will look completely different.
"Play with it," he stressed.
But the most important thing to me was the following advice: "First you have to know the rules perfectly."
"Only then can you hurt her," Jakub said.
I finally understand why we have to put all these teachings together, what you can combine with what and why, even if you often see something completely different in fashion journals.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to the photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared much more clothing variants than he finally photographs.
So for a ten-page fashion story (say ten outfits) you need to be prepared to style at least fifteen.
And also that the clothing on the photo in combination with other accessories sometimes looks quite different than in reality.
All of this must be taken into account in the design of the outfit.
That image and style sometimes make up half of the success, Jan Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD> also confirmed this.
All you need to do is look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer whose image and marketing have made her a world star.
