IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
Founded a hundred years ago in New York City, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was not until 1924 that the name IBM was adopted – it was originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous stick card clocks to record the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of the rival company, to help him lead the company.
This leader then even overshadowed the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas to this day, the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM began, as the name suggests, with the manufacture and distribution of all kinds of machines for trading - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson ran the company, he doubled its sales to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped guide NASA's flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the famous man's flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same computer architecture – the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of that time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it acquired the consultancy part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers, thereby fully entering the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off over the past three years is the “Smart Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a wise way in areas not even planned before, for example to improve the situation in traffic and in city administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the platform "Smart Commerce", which is intended to help traders guide the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and has a world-class research team dedicated to the technology of voice recognition.
