Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five licensed state travel agencies in the then <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly sold only travel to the socialist eastern bloc countries, in the West at that time only the chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even the citizens of the Eastern Bloc (including the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called currency pledge - the condition for an exit to the West - was given only to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange pledge.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the countryside, it is no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and cottages - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is not even aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the obligation to exchange currencies in neighbouring Western European countries has been lifted, resulting in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
When traveling to Paris, Czech travelers slept in the tent in the park, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or pension at the time.
A typical feature of Czech foreign trips at the time was a suitcase full of canned food, beer and permanent sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus also our average wages increased, leading to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began to regularly prepare for charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-satin" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have flown annually to distant sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitively one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per person for a single holiday stay including the cost of the resort.
