21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
Von Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with heights, depths and happy ends: the Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and bare.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussel World Exhibition is a striking and famous example.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered to be a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian Pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like auxiliary construction in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the world exhibition in the Swiss garden at the Wiener Südbahnhof and rebuilt and opened in 1962 in it a museum of the 20th century - the "20th house" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used for so long until contemporary art got a new home in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a case of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate art historian with a considerable career in youth as an ice skating runner, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, firmly established the renovation with politicians and monument protectors.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a café and a bookstore, and an office house had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small state
For the implementation, Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he sensibly rebuilt and expanded Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was a "hugely important place" for him, where he had "almost every weekend" looked at the exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
There were far greater problems with the current renovation: the building was “an energy smuggler,” says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, insulated glass reinforced with fiberglass and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light pit between the house and the street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the lightweight tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust-proof paint.
And the cinema room is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small staff.
"Often we had to find a material that is good and cheap and also liked the monumental protection," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building remains flexible and lightweight.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants "to awaken a real awareness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because an urban accident has occurred: around the Swiss garden, the completely redesigned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential houses, is being created.
And another chance will perhaps come: the 21st House could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood location in the Swiss garden.
