Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She combined the image of a secretive and solid, but also elaborate Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she wanted to become a very big number in investment banking as well.
In 2007, UBS managed more money for wealthy customers than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, it was advanced as an investment bank into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That was impressive.
Hans Geiger, former banker and later long-time professor of banking in Zurich, says: "I always set UBS as a model for a good bank to my students at the time."
"From today's point of view, one wonders: How could I be so wrong?"
He made a huge mistake.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something was wrong with UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker.
A few months later, he was wondering why he had left.
The bank’s investment department had been screwed with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase in the amount of sage and writes in 13 billion francs.
In fact, she found investors for this, but ones that some people would have been upset until recently: an opaque Asian government fund from Singapore and an Arab government fund that was so secret that you didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billions of dollars in losses, and CEO Marcel Ospel, Switzerland’s second-best-paid board of directors, resigned in 2006.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS, in the face of its poor investments in the financial crisis, was in danger of collapse and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, and the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a compulsory convertible bond, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken – for it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to host such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS in 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see chart).
"Once again, we couldn't save UBS," says bank researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS capitulated in a tax dispute with America and declared itself ready to release the data of wealthy customers who may have been collecting taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million – as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty.
Thus, UBS was more or less openly known to have helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for wealthy customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, the Swiss banking secret was no longer the same.
It was followed by the resignation of the Chairman of the Board of Directors and the Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both key areas of business: in investment banking through misspelling and in asset management through tax evasion.
And just as it got a little quieter again, just as you thought UBS would get it back, then follows this unhappy trader story: A single trader fucks up 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes something is going wrong.
And it turns out: with risk management in investment banking, it obviously still doesn’t work.
"With the Adoboli case, it has been found that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and finance professor at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The financial director of a large German bank is also sure: “The problem with UBS is that it has no control over risk control.”
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago set out to become guardians of the great wealth of the world: no too great risks, but security for money - even if the world collapsed beyond the Alpine Republic.
The vaults of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich still fits the cliché of the wealthy Swiss private bank - it is only a little bigger.
Already the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich Railway Road, which leads directly from the main station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are luxurious, the store rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany's can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as the Sprüngli confectionery.
For centuries, Swiss banks have resided here: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse, to elite private banks such as Julius Bär.
The reception hall of the UBS is accessed by a heavy turning door.
Inside the walls are covered with marble, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, next to the bench logo a large sign to the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has been suppressed by both Swiss major banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point – or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, he does business, like all Swiss bankers, also with the two major banks.
The UBS has become much too large, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if so, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, first yielding high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss grand bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven million-country decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to 68 billion francs, or about 45 billion euros, were approved by the politicians to save the bankruptcy of the large bank.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three Swiss major banks merged into a huge group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for the small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and was growing.
The two different predecessors banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but dormant bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of money, with which they could spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
"I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team," says banking researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, humble, who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man who has worked his way up from banking to the very top."
But Ospel finally relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," says Geiger.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear: arrogance came before the case.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings, at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: “Goldman Sachs gets off the throne.”
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the "League Tables", the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That’s where UBS wanted to go, all the way up.
Some of her steps were already successful.
She played a leading role in foreign exchange and stock trading.
However, company consultants who were commissioned pointed out a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banking language "Fixed Income", there is a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost them existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime investments.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed on securities on to American mortgage loans – but also held risks.
Even when other banks have long been looking for a way out.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the U.S. real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” says bank expert Geiger.
So great is the euphoria, so deep is the case.
One manager after the other had to go when the attempts to clean up were more difficult than thought.
Positions at UBS have become a sliding seat and are shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He has to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the underlying business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: an end to investment banking, a focus on asset management, a return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is supposed to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
On Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, will present to the world his future strategy.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has established himself: he is supposed to permanently manage the business of UBS, the Zurich bank said on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants the investment bank to return to the status quo in the mid-1990s.
3500 posts he deletes.
But that will not be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money from?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is sure to ask himself right now.
So far, he has only said that he and his wife will first look for an apartment in Zurich.
