Smart Crows Spread in Cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": but the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts say.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities residents complain about the dirt and noise of animals.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer to be taken out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian emptiness.
There, experts from all over the federal territory advised on possible exits.
You are looking for alternatives in cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the land flight of the specially protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture increasingly destroyed the traditional habitats.
Hunting, growing crops and falling typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs are found, among others, in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest, among others, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
In 2005, a controversial project on the mass killing of crows in the county had created negative headlines.
Critics had described the capture of animals in bird traps and the killing with buds as particularly brutal.
"The normal displacement, the crimping, does not bring anything," the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver found out of nowhere.
Nesting nests with water or falling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals fade away, large colonies split up and spread to other places."
Agglomeration is conceivable only as an exception in hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away."
Without the surroundings, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable a combination of grazing the animals from sensitive living areas and lure offers to resettle them in other places.
"Info boards instead of chainsaws" on the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens warns for a completely different handling of the animals: "A pimple in the face can be best tolerated in the end with self-confidence."
In Schleswig-Holstein, Jürgens had co-founded the Asheberg Crow Training Path, where signposts inform about the life of highly intelligent seed cranes.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their own tool as an aid.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of birds reaches.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to use stones to bring a scaffold to the collapse in order to get to a moth larvae.
Without a lot of training, they realized purposefully what size and shape a stone must have in order for the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the crows had to solve a more complicated problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had wired them.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle of the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even succeeded in this at first.
