That’s easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found it wasn’t difficult to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately pinpoint their desired demographics with scientific accuracy — as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing fan groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the adds invited users to a survey asking about their educational status, their attitude to violence, and their assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more sensible, more democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as likes, text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s data supernova is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers named after this page in the title rise by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this site you can study people that you usually don’t reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you tried to interview people of the British National Party earlier, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have given them access,” Bartlett says.
“With Facebook, all that goes away – you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site provides an opportunity to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full-length on Facebook were significantly more likely to have problems with drinking than students who were silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that peer-to-peer students, such as residential counselors, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook is also constantly collecting the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data only Facebook has access to – digital freedom champions have long known that the site should make its big data pit accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want it or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to share their own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how many of the information in a user profile and in posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still taking place offline.”
