And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about swings at school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they are well-suited to their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and swinging are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies have shown that we lie 10 to 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are seen as emergencies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or “discovering lies” is one that is important to learn for every person, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as charades, in which the goal is to call out "Have You!", the unmasking of deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades from respected universities, in particular, the field of physiology and the far-reaching research projects in which Physiology, Physiology, and Physiology are involved.
One result of the research is that most of the ancient myths about lying have been unmasked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don’t always snore, stumble, blush, and tingle.
However, we cannot conclude from this that these liars are difficult to detect and unmask.
A trained liar can penetrate the truth by learning something about the structure of the assertion, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years investigating the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of disguise. And it is clear that disguising a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to cope in our complex world, especially when advising or questioning individuals or negotiating on their own.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, arousing their interest and mastering their own emotions. And they feel intuitively how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people that men are more likely to list “self-centered” lies than women whose lies are more “orientated to others” – as a rule, they want to protect the feelings of others – that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people.
We also know that when a person has been exposed as a criminal, others feel less guilty of having lied to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of that person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent assessment of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone is usually constantly tripping with their foot so that they don’t unfairly accuse them of tripping with their foot during a meeting.
