The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the first percent of people in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, because from January to March 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloa had no employment, which is 4,53 percent of the working population in September.
Less liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economics scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), commented that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
