In the draft lawsuit drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the Decree-Law unconstitutional, as the Commission Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for the regulations relating to radio and television.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Decree-Law. After the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree-Law and stopped all activities for the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without taking part in the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the national government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take with general regulations.
She also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it manages the affairs of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, and it results in better use of the radio spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitization, which is a decision in the public interest that has not only technical aspects, "because it encompasses economic, social, political and security-technical aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a set of features that put the constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already carried out the digital transformation through the government, even though they had highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government interferes in the competences of Congress with the issuance of the contested legislative decree, because the laws adopted by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
