Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his home doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on and controlled four times.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal physician, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplasticas to determine the reason for his pain and loss of muscle in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want to do so because he considered him innocent.
He was operated on four times on tongue cancer and lost 18 kilograms of weight, in addition to other conditions such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood flow problems in the legs, the doctor noted.
Fujimori has been in the detention center Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian Army Death Squad, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin its visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which, according to the president of Uruguay, will be the highlight of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón’s support regarding the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still appear to be tax havens from the international community, a statement rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and industrialized countries in the world, and since January of this year there has been an agreement on exchanging tax information to avoid double investment with the South American country.
In recent years, the government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the implementation of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), including countries that have not implemented all international standards on cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The bearded installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
