Trinihove has helped 6,000 young people threatened with social exclusion
The organization was created to prevent the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social welfare organization Trinijove have led to important results: In this quarter-century, 6,000 young people, threatened with social exclusion, were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, a balance sheet was drawn yesterday at an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low level of education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginality.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous heads of institutions that have worked with the association for 25 years.
The participation of political representatives from different directions during election campaigns proved the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol took part in the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The Grand Hall of Fabra i Coats was also attended by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the General Director of the Social Work of the Sparkasse La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinihove was created in very difficult times and that the present times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far "is a good foundation".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinihove is an example that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the club and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house, where gigantic parties were held, was cleared
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The twelve occupiers left the building yesterday afternoon without any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had occupied illegally and in which they had organized huge festivals that had driven the neighborhood to despair. The evacuation took place on judicial order without police intervention.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the house manager confirmed.
The occupants, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply, painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
Huge parties were held on the three lower floors, lasting up to two days, and driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the beginning of the occupation of the house.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the occupants of the house made their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while these in the discotheque cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the recreational space had been indicated by the neighbors for rest disturbance, while according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the occupiers of the house and in particular from the guests of the parties organized there, and which, according to the statements of the angry neighbors, became more and more in the last weeks.
The head of the discotheque said the harassment had been so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that it has received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
Last week, the chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in Barcelona's city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, called for the immediate removal of the building and the control of the problems of civic coexistence and the downfall of the district.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the occupants had penetrated all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and take action against the asocial acts in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 3.30 p.m., police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who had watched four people attempt to break into the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
A park or a mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The urban call for proposals on the 16 gates opens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona anew.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its smear paper on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in numbers to Central Park in New York.
With the collapse of the CMB in 1987, the park became in the eyes of many again the upper limit of Barcelona, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that spreads not in the north-south direction, but up (mountains) and down (sea).
The classification of Collserolas as a natural park plays with this idea.
The role of the yogi bear was no longer played by the Central Park, but by Yellowstone with wild boars.
That was the point when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate points to the concept of a park.
Either that's it, or someone's planning to put gates on the ground.
The question arises: Collserola, park or mountain?
The invitation to tender is not only from an organizational point of view, but also in view of a reflection on the city, the topic of conversation in the mouth of all Barcelona architects.
It’s almost a recurring topic that two members of this old-groomed caste, who meet in the elevator, can turn to.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the fabric for one of the rare matches between what three architects from Barcelona think about it, and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán "it is necessary", after the attack on the coast, to talk about the "front on the mountains", insofar as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, who has not been delivered about the green apples.
"One should assume that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex,” the architect judges, for whom the title “Gate of Collserola” contains a “lexical trap”: one should not “imagine it as access to a park, but as a limitation of areas in which action must be taken.”
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban planning experience, considers the proposal to be an “intellectual challenge” that entails “some dangers”.
Dangers due to the "uncertainty that the design of a public space brings with it nowadays" following the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the area of the forum.
The first fear is one’s own limitation on what can be built.
“Limiting something always means setting the next step,” i.e., crossing it.
"You have to think about new urban planning tools, because the current ones [regarding the General Metropolitano (PGM) plan] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who adheres more closely to the question, thinks, simplified, that the side of Collserola, which goes towards Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that does not go towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the patronage of Collserola, which should not "bump into deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for having given his board the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
He also notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guiding letter that allows the architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubt" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("the right thing," he says) should be a "only for Architek."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, as Collserola's global view is lacking in the terms of the tender: "There have been 16 competitions tendered in cross-section," he says, "on the Axis Mountain-Sea. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area as a whole."
This, at least in his case, has led him to participate in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next door.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped in its entire length in such a way that a smooth transition between the city and green areas is created.
Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal who comes free
After 72 days of silence, Casino Red’s attorney freed the brother of the Mayor of Monterrey from the trial that is being conducted against him for alleged blackmail.
After 72 days of imprisonment, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal is released after being pardoned by Casino Red’s agent before the Second District Criminal Court, which is conducting the trial against the Mayor of Monterrey’s brother for blackmail.
After the assassination of Casino Royale, Sergio Gil García, the owner of Casino Red, published a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás allegedly forcing him to pay a sum of money so that the city administration would approve the secret operation of the betting house.
After the criminal complaint, the prosecutor’s office opened a criminal case against the brother of the panist mayor, who was arrested on September 2 for 30 days.
After four hours with the official of the Ministerio Público 3 en Delitos Patrimoniales, he was taken to Casa de Arraigo 1 in the Old Quarter of the capital.
He remained at this place for 49 days after a second warrant, after the official of the Ministerio Público had dismissed the crimes for bribery and organized crime.
