Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which Government Secretary Francisco Blake and seven other people died.
The Secretaria de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat for Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation into the accident in which the Secretary of the Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died, indicated that the helicopter with its entire undamaged structure can crash a arrow land directly against the ground, without the need for a landfall.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before launch that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing was in contact with trees at 25 meters high, with the helicopter losing its hull, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why he met all the conditions for the transportation of personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigation into the area where the machine had landed.
"During the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the surcharge affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
Currently, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but they can take several months, perhaps even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial flew at travel speed and the plane fell on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the collision."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, included six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visibility:
In accordance with flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of sight flight, which means that the crew must have had sufficient sight during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the launch, with some deep-hanging clouds rising as it proceeded towards the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that because of the clouds, the team had chosen a lower area with better visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Point of impact:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are consistent, and there may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or a deviation from the flight route prior to the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date indicates that the helicopter was impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of the scattered airplane remains suggest that the helicopter with its intact structure was impacted on the ground.
No signs of fire or explosion:
The remains of the plane at the crash site do not close to fire or explosion.
The latest test results indicate several ground contacts.
During the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is steep and has an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a meticulous search in an area beyond the locked area at the crash site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the undamaged aircraft structure had hit the ground.
MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Security Agency of Mexico is conducting a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by specialists of the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the IMSS sports grounds in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuauhtémoc sports ground (in the west of the state of Mexico) and will continue since October 8 at the Nezahualcóyolt sports ground (in the east of the state of Mexico).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and conclude on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to get to know the factors and the role of genetics associated with the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that it is aimed at that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should complete nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He further concluded that on those Saturdays the subjects measured (weight, size, waist circumference), controlled their blood pressure and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes associated with obesity in childhood).
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of the concerns of health professionals about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that one Mexican is on average 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity is expressed in the inability to burn out the excess energy (calories) that we take, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors explain to the parents all the results of the measurements and suggest to them lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using transportation rather than walking short distances.
