Asphalt from UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs that emerge from the road surface were fully observed, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 impact holes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico.
In his lecture "Blowholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera suggested that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthens. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic tensile behavior.
The resilient behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very resilient and at 50° C. almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer concluded.
The FQ researcher noted that the roads of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt-built and then hardened stones.
Every single stone of this layer of wear was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good force distribution in the road surface.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed,” said the chemical engineer.
"Above the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
Which receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs a suitable thickness and the material of which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further, important factors to consider, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates the layer and is difficult to get out again, which causes a softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of impact holes.
If a punching hole is formed," he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that in order to avoid frequent impact holes these regulations are complied with.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
