This was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A lophoscopist from Cali entered history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4th, a lophoscopist of the Investigative Unit of the Prosecutor's Office (CTI) from Cali entered as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI’s department, Eliasar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years, had a standby service this week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the campaign against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliasar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
On Friday night he flew by helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one could be the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he should take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, because it was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a peasant in the area, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
Fingerprints do not lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell and a flashlight, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of telling Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that he was actually the head of the FARC.
In Search of Traces
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the recognition given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in solving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murders and robberies, and confirm the identity of the persons arrested.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false IDs or have none.
We'll take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in the event of a theft, because the thief had leaned right there with his hand when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by bottles of wine.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member could be suspicious, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the killer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object using chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a plant cell or ribbon is used to carry them.
Afterwards, the prints are sent to Asif, the criminal database, or to the police station.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without IDs," the CTI expert said.
He said that not everything is as it would be depicted in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, so not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if a corresponding comparison is made.
