It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an occasion to reflect on this issue as well as on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will bear fruit only if it explores the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution drives a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to renounce a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce steadily electricity without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climate irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which makes its decision subject to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which just now intends to build only the latest generation of nuclear power plants.
