Although the German model, which is oriented towards renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence on imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in wind energy, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; on the basis of this, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the sustainability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price in the globalized economy plays a key role in competitiveness as well as in the stability of industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay as much as they are resisting the principle of this energy source.
