The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of security is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent inspections in existing plants, such as at the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, which have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are obsessed with the idea of security.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious disruptions.
Only one, namely Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was summoned by reactor construction as well as inexorable, human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as the cooperation of the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a draft that allows it to be resilient to such phenomena.
