Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading police, judiciary and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to the numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France itself had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students by the authorities had shaped the weekly shows, the interior minister had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "did not need any talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right, the voice of Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people, including more than 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left, was struck by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 had stated that France "cannot take up all the poverty of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
Fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left in 2005.
From both camps, immigrants were perceived as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to trivialities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point to us in a recently published work, which summarizes the latest findings regarding immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a confluence of positives among the specials.
Restricting immigration would weaken growth and harm the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the notion that they threaten to replace the local workforce, especially the less skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience has shown that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage earners, as they focus heavily on occupations in sectors that are unburdened by workplace technology.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage-earners, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not equal to the job offer.
Positive salary effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
In this way, Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in the immigrant flow will result in a related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought in by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas as well as economic growth (a high proportion of nationalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
