Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It will supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to commit this event with splendor and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on the Baltic Sea coast with orchestral sound and fine-tasting buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve that transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas will be delivered to Western Europe each year through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already have the possibility of building a third line on the route itself.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this huge structure seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not shy about comparing the Nord Stream pipeline with a “new German-Soviet pact” in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a deconsolidation of European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has achieved its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries that have strong gas consumption and their gas reserves are dwindling.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete cladding, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During its construction, minefields dating back to World War II had to be evaded.
“Around a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed because of caution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, reinforced measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long string of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently settling at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be unlikely, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes from a sea vessel, and by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, has a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipe and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal on arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated here (respectively at 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunion and the French group of companies GDF Suez (respectively at 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on an extendable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas actually transported," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs for both pipelines are expected to amount to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are determined to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline is located on a sandy, pine forested coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other metrics of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a trademark notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give the writing a new style again.
It has a flair of adventure, with hours spent writing at candlelight.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular inlay, its rubber band, the egg shell-colored sides, as it ages over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, at the time decided to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company’s specialist consultant, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton varnish used, for example, for covering upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was very popular among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has resurrected an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now head of brand at Modo Modo.
Success comes in.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom image of buyers, as the notebook fascinates businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially employed 12 people, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookshops, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centers and understands how to enforce its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the time and its new need for writing, which exists despite the rise of emails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour" in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, the company also released a leopard pattern cover.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural spirit and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer covers... The brand has the entire range of articles.
In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, which is today Syntegra Capital, thus opening a new chapter in the history of the company Moleskine.
